1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:20,000
Most teams do not have an LLM problem. They have an LLM operations problem.
This is llm_gateway: one endpoint to manage all your LLM traffic with routing,
failover, policy control, caching, and observability.

2
00:00:20,000 --> 00:00:50,000
Without a gateway, auth patterns drift, costs become unclear, and debugging is hard.
llm_gateway centralizes control so teams can govern model access consistently.

3
00:00:50,000 --> 00:01:25,000
The Go backend exposes familiar chat and embedding endpoints.
A Next.js dashboard manages providers, routes, API keys, spend groups,
cache settings, and audit logs.

4
00:01:25,000 --> 00:02:00,000
In Providers, you can register multiple LLM backends and monitor health.
The gateway tracks failures, applies retries, and supports failover for resilience.

5
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:40,000
Routes let you map a stable slug to provider and model configuration.
You can apply system prompts, token limits, and fallback providers
without changing application code.

6
00:02:40,000 --> 00:03:10,000
For security, llm_gateway supports JWT and gateway API keys.
Keys can be scoped by provider and model, with rate limits and request controls.

7
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:45,000
Cost rules are defined per provider and model.
Spend is estimated from token usage and can be grouped by team or project
for practical chargeback.

8
00:03:45,000 --> 00:04:20,000
Redis caching improves repeated non-stream chat performance and lowers token spend.
Audit logs capture end-to-end request traces for debugging and compliance.

9
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:50,000
Market LLM offerings are endpoints.
llm_gateway is a control plane across endpoints:
provider-neutral, operations-first, and governance-ready.

10
00:04:50,000 --> 00:05:00,000
With llm_gateway, teams deliver GenAI faster with better reliability,
cost control, and platform-level visibility.
